      label: "Getting there",
      body: "From Watch Hill: 30 minutes via I-95 W to exit 92, then Route 2 W. Parking at Foxwoods is free across multiple covered decks — the Grand Pequot Tower deck and the Fox Tower deck are the most central. You do not need to stay overnight to park; day visitors are explicitly welcome. Avoid Friday evening arrivals if possible; concert and gaming traffic on Route 2 can back up.",
    },
    {
      label: "The casino floor — what to know if you're new",
      body: "<strong>Gambling age is 21</strong> for all table games, slots, and the race book. Bingo is 18. The casino floor is free to walk through, free to watch, and free to enter — you only spend money if you gamble or buy food. There's no dress code on the gaming floor. ATMs are everywhere but the fees are high; bring cash or use the bank-style cashier cages where withdrawals are cheaper. New gamblers: blackjack tables typically have the lowest house edge among the main games.",
    },
    {
      label: "Best time to visit",
      body: "<strong>Weekday afternoons</strong> are the most relaxed — lighter crowds at the casino, easier reservations at the better restaurants, no concert traffic. <strong>Weekend evenings</strong> are the most energetic — full casino floor, concerts at Grand Theater, packed restaurants. <strong>Sunday brunch</strong> at Cedars Steaks & Oysters is a quiet local secret. The Mashantucket Pequot Museum is least crowded on weekday mornings.",
    },
    {
      label: "Where to eat",
      body: "Foxwoods has 35+ restaurants ranging from food court to fine dining. The serious dinner options: <strong>Cedars Steaks & Oysters</strong> for the upscale steakhouse experience, <strong>Al Dente</strong> for southern Italian, <strong>Paragon</strong> at the top of the Fox Tower for high-end with views. <strong>Hard Rock Cafe</strong> is the reliable mid-tier choice. The <strong>food court</strong> is more interesting than most casino food courts — there are several genuinely good quick-service options. Avoid Sugar Factory unless you're committed to that specific bachelorette aesthetic.",
    },
    {
      label: "Non-gambling things to do",
      body: "If you don't gamble at all, you can still spend a full day here: the <strong>Pequot Museum</strong> (3 hours), <strong>Tanger Outlets</strong> shopping (1-2 hours, 70+ stores), <strong>Foxwoods HighFlyer zipline</strong> (the largest in Connecticut, launched from the 33-story Fox Tower), the <strong>Thrill Tower</strong> (Sky Drop and Sky Launch), <strong>Monza karting</strong>, <strong>TopGolf Swing Suite</strong>, <strong>High Roller Luxury Lanes</strong> bowling, and the <strong>G Spa</strong>. The casino's <strong>Grand Theater</strong> hosts major touring acts; check the schedule before your visit.",
    },
    {
      label: "Mohegan Sun vs Foxwoods",
      body: "The two casinos are 15 minutes apart and very different. Foxwoods is larger, more spread out, more family-friendly, and has the museum. Mohegan Sun is more concentrated, has a flashier casino floor, and is generally considered to have a better restaurant lineup. If you can only visit one, Foxwoods is the better choice for a day trip; Mohegan Sun is better as an overnight party destination. If you have time, do both — they're an easy combined day.",
    },
  ],
  cta: {
    framing:
      "Most Watch Hill visitors do Foxwoods as a day trip and return to the village in the evening. If you want to stay overnight at Foxwoods itself, the on-property hotels are mid-range. But Watch Hill remains the better base for almost everything else in the area.",
    label: "Browse Watch Hill stays →",
    url: affiliates.hotels.allWatchHill,
  },
  faqs: [
    {
      q: "How far is Foxwoods from Watch Hill, Rhode Island?",
      a: "About 25 miles or 30 minutes by car. The route runs through Mystic, then up Route 2 W into Mashantucket. There's no public transit from Watch Hill — you'll need a car. Many Watch Hill hotels can arrange car service if requested.",
    },
    {
      q: "Is Foxwoods worth visiting if I don't gamble?",
      a: "Yes. The Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center is one of the most substantive Native American museums in the country and is the standout reason to visit even for non-gamblers. The complex also has Tanger Outlets shopping, the HighFlyer zipline, Thrill Tower attractions, multiple restaurants, and the Grand Theater for concerts. A full day at Foxwoods without gambling is genuinely possible.",
    },
    {
      q: "What is the Mashantucket Pequot Museum?",
      a: "It's the Tribe's own history museum — one of the largest Native American museums in the country, opened in 1998 on the reservation. Permanent exhibits cover 18,000 years of Indigenous history in the region, including the Pequot War, the near-destruction and modern revitalization of the Tribe, and a 185-foot observation tower with panoramic views. Allow 2-3 hours. Admission is around $20 for adults.",
    },
    {
      q: "How many casinos are at Foxwoods?",
      a: "Six casinos under one roof, plus a separate race book and one of the world's largest bingo halls (3,600 seats). The complex has more than 250 table games covering 22 game types, including 100 poker tables. Foxwoods is the largest casino resort in North America.",
    },
    {
      q: "What's the gambling age at Foxwoods?",
      a: "21 for all table games, slots, the race book, and Keno. The legal age for Bingo is 18. ID is checked at the door if you look anywhere close to the line.",
    },
    {
      q: "Is parking free at Foxwoods?",
      a: "Yes — parking is free across multiple covered parking decks. Day visitors are explicitly welcome; you do not need to be a hotel guest to park or to use the casinos, restaurants, or attractions. The most central decks are at the Grand Pequot Tower and Fox Tower.",
    },
    {
      q: "Should I visit Foxwoods or Mohegan Sun?",
      a: "Foxwoods is larger, more spread out, has the museum, and is more family-friendly. Mohegan Sun is more concentrated, has a generally better restaurant lineup, and a flashier atmosphere. They're 15 minutes apart on Route 2 — many visitors who have time do both on the same trip. For a single day trip from Watch Hill with non-gambling activity, Foxwoods is the better choice.",
    },
    {
      q: "Is Foxwoods open year-round?",
      a: "Yes — Foxwoods operates 24/7, 365 days a year. The casinos never close. Some specific restaurants, attractions, and concert schedules vary; check the calendar before specific bookings.",
    },
  ],
  related: [
    { href: "/blog/day-trips-from-watch-hill", tag: "All Day Trips", title: "10 Best Day Trips from Watch Hill" },
    { href: "/blog/mystic-day-trip", tag: "Halfway There", title: "A Perfect Day in Mystic, CT" },
    { href: "/blog/where-to-stay-watch-hill", tag: "Stay Local", title: "Where to Stay in Watch Hill" },
    { href: "/blog/best-restaurants-watch-hill", tag: "Better Food", title: "15 Best Restaurants in Watch Hill" },
  ],
};
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
  <Nav />
  <main>
    <AttractionPost {...props} />
  </main>
</Base>
